<font color="#FF0000">BIRDMEN TWO FOUR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Aug 18 12:24:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Been there Birdman; <br>
Operation Knox, we carried seven charred bodies out of a downed puff plane, all of them stuffed into two burlap bags and hand carried down the mountain that had taken us three days to climb. Have never forgotten that smell that stayed with us for days.<br>
But, you guys were my heroes.  <br>
When I returned from R&amp;R and found our M-60 filthy with caked carbon on account we hadn't been resupplied with ceaning gear it was an airmen who I never really thanked at An Hoa who provided us with some high grade aviation fuel to help clean them.<br>
Ripped the crud right off in two easy dumpings. We had the cleanest and most reliable guns in the company.<br>
There were other airmen that are unforgettable in my life, when I was medevacked with Jungle rot to Chu Lai, Docs wanted color pictures of my feet on account they had never seen a multi-colored immersion foot problem like mine, some Airmen found out from a buddy of mine that worked on aircraft's that I was a grunt and all the birdmen came around picked me up took me to their club. <br>
Honored me as if I was the hero. Said, they only saw us from the air as little ants, had never seen a real grunt before. I couldn't understand why many of them didn't believe they were doing much for the war effort. Most felt that way because they hadn't engaged the enemy &quot;eye ball to eye ball&quot; as Ed mentions. Hey, I took advantage of their feeling of failure and had another beer, on them of course. <br>
But I tell you; I learned to respect those that maintained those lifesavers as well as those who flew them. <br><br>
In Nam there was nothing like looking at the pilot of a plane that just dropped his load on an entrenched enemy and he gave us the thumbs up, WHAT A RUSH, that was to the grunts (we were easily amused). <br>
.<br>
Here's an account of what happened on November 8, 1967 we had been pinned down for hours and expecting the NVA to make a mad rush toward us for the river that was to our backs.<br><br>
.<br>
From Dreams of Glory, Clear Fields of Fire, copyright Cook Barela 1997.<br>
.<br><br>
&quot;Keeton who had his gun team set up to our left side was laying on his back smoking a Kool cigarette when he motioned for us to look up. Two camouflaged phantom jets appeared out of a clear dark blue sky. They dropped straight down toward the tree line directly in front of us, and pulled out only a few hundred feet above ground level. The thundering roar of their exhaust shook the ground and as they pulled out, the trees were left vibrating.<br>
&quot; Such display of power must have had a devastating and fearful effect upon the enemy,&quot; I was thinking when Keeton spoke. <br>
&quot;They were only marking their target, that was their dry run. Now they'll come in for the kill.&quot; No sooner had Keeton spoke, when we caught the sun's reflection off the shinny gray and green colored aircraft as they turned slowly and effortlessly in the air and dropped again.  A couple of hundred feet off the ground, each of the planes dropped two long olive drab colored barrel shaped canisters. They pulled up just as effortlessly as they had before but this time the noise of their engines was muted by the explosive roar of four powerful and violent explosions. <br>
Before us, the sky was ripped apart as the ground and tree line met it in a series of fierce fierily balls. A blinding ball of yellow and blistering red light spewed death and destruction over the entire area. It was as if a miniature atomic bomb had been dropped right in front of us. The ground below us shook and bounced us off the ground. Whining, sizzling burning shrapnel came flying through the air right toward us. A large chunk of metal embedded itself deep into the ground just a few feet from where we were. &quot;Gosh, damn them, don't they know we're here,&quot; Perry behind our gun team cried out. The planes had dropped four canisters of napalm. Liquid fire, hot burning napalm was much like getting droplets of melting plastic on you, but unlike plastic, the blistering acid just keeps burning, melting skin and bone together. <br>
When the napalm bombs exploded a Hugh fiery ball arose high into the air. A second later the intense heat wave of the exploding bombs covered us. It was as if someone had sucked all the air out of the area yet we were still about a football fields length away from where the actual bombs had been dropped. I could not imagine anyone living through such a fiery inferno. <br>
The phantom jets circled again and again until they had dropped their sixth and final load. The treeline where the gooks had been burned like the fires of hell. The planes then circled once more came in slow and began to turn into a wide curve. They arched their planes until they were both flying side by side in a clockwise direction. At about 11:00 O'clock they turned their bellies toward the sun caught its reflective glow, dropped their right wings and WAVED GOOD-BY twice to us as they disappeared into the dark smoke filled sky.&quot;<br><br>
Bill, it was all a united effort; we all served in different ways. But it was my commitment to Bro and others that cause me to go on with my life. They paid the price and I owed it to them to make something of my life in honor of them. To live fully the life they were denied. What others think has no weight compared to the military men that were killed or wounded in helping end the war.<br><br>

